My opinion is that we should troll for topics and volunteers, then fix
on a date once we've got a good agenda lined up.  I think a powerful
lineup is more important than regularity--for me, anyway.

How far in advance do you have to book a room, Eric?

I polled the team I work with and we came up with a list of possible topics:

SOLR/Sphinx
Behavior Driven Development
Integration with SOAP services (a.k.a. being enterprisey)
Rails 2.0 (what to expect, advantages, directions)
JRuby (and/or Rubinus, alternative Ruby implementations)
Deployment environments
RESTful web services
Localization/Globalize
Writing Rake tasks
Using Rails with/on Amazon Web Services
Contributing to Rails and other open source projects (writing patches)
Developing widgets for social networks (Facebook, OpenSocial, other)

Anybody have anything to contribute on these subjects?  Would coverage
of any of these compel you to attend a meeting?

What are other folks interested in that we missed?

Cheers,
Jonathan

